2026-03-20T16:42:20.973Z JOY-0007 item.created "Add short flags to frequently used CLI parameters" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T16:42:28.396Z JOY-0007 comment.added "Many flags in joy ls (and likely other commands) lack short forms: --tree, --status, --priority, --mine, --blocked, --milestone, --tag, --parent. Clap supports POSIX-style flag bundling automatically, so -St for --short --tree would work once short flags exist. Decision needed: which flags get short forms? Two approaches discussed: (1) boolean flags get short forms, value flags stay long-only; (2) frequently used flags get short forms regardless of type. Resolve --show/-s vs --status/-s conflict (--status is more common, consider reassigning)." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T16:43:48.189Z JOY-0007 item.updated "Review CLI parameter ergonomics (short flags, bundling)" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:06:31.658Z JOY-0008 item.created "joy ai setup re-asks for already configured AI tools" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:06:37.468Z JOY-0008 comment.added "On re-run, joy ai setup asks 'Configure? [Y/n]' again for tools that are already set up. Expected: show 'configured' and silently update joy-owned files (skills, permissions). Only prompt for newly detected, unconfigured tools. A --force flag could override to reconfigure everything." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:11:22.429Z JOY-0009 item.created "Automated validation for CLI-testable steps in milestone checklists" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:13:17.260Z JOY-0009 comment.added "Needs careful consideration. Manual validation is highly valuable because: (1) the tester experiences the product end-to-end as a real user, (2) unexpected issues surface that no checklist anticipates (we found multiple bugs and UX improvements during our first manual validation run), (3) it forces the responsible person to actually use their own solution. Automation should only cover the mechanical parts (does the command run, does the file exist) and never replace the manual walkthrough. The goal is to reduce tedium, not to skip the experience." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:21:59.802Z JOY-000A item.created "Config defaults: init with all values, code fallback, auto-update on new keys" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:22:08.192Z JOY-000A comment.added "Three parts: (1) joy init writes config.yaml with all known default values, not a minimal file. (2) joy config get uses fallback chain: config file -> environment -> code default. Never returns exit 1 for known keys. (3) On tool update (any joy command), automatically append new config keys with their defaults to existing config.yaml. No explicit refresh command needed -- users would forget it. This also fixes the UX issue where AI tools see 'Error: Exit code 1' when querying unset but known config keys." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:35:21.683Z JOY-000B item.created "AI does not suggest size when creating items via skill" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T17:35:27.419Z JOY-000B comment.added "The Joy skill prompt instructs the AI to suggest a size (1-7) for new items, but in practice the AI skips it. The skill planning section mentions size but the item creation section does not explicitly remind the AI to include --size in the joy add call. Fix: add explicit size guidance to the 'Planning and creating items' section of the skill." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T19:43:13.058Z JOY-000E item.created "Replace serde_yml (unmaintained, unsound) with alternative" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T19:43:19.225Z JOY-000E comment.added "GitHub Dependabot flagged serde_yml and its dependency libyml as unmaintained and unsound (1 high, 1 medium). Affects both joy-core and jot-core. Candidates: serde_yaml_ng (maintained fork), serde_yaml (original, check status). Must be replaced in joy-core first, then jot-core follows via dependency update." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T19:45:12.944Z JOY-000F item.created "Config layering: separate project and personal settings" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T19:45:25.307Z JOY-000F comment.added "Problem: joy config set writes to .joy/config.yaml which is committed to Git. Personal preferences (output.short, output.emoji, output.fortune) end up affecting all team members. A developer changed short=true in the jot repo and it would have been pushed to everyone.

Prior art:
- git: .git/config (local, not pushed) vs ~/.gitconfig (global)
- env files: .env (committed) vs .env.local (gitignored)

Options discussed:
1. .joy/config.local.yaml -- gitignored, personal overrides. joy init adds it to .gitignore automatically.
2. joy config set --global -- writes to ~/.config/joy/config.yaml instead of project config
3. Key categorization -- some keys are inherently personal (output.*), some are project-wide (project.prefix, agents.*). joy config set could warn or auto-route based on category.

Fallback chain should be: .joy/config.local.yaml > .joy/config.yaml > ~/.config/joy/config.yaml > code defaults.

Related to JOY-000A (config defaults) and JOY-0002 (joy project get/set). This story covers the layering concept, the others cover specific aspects." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-20T19:55:44.438Z JOY-000F comment.added "Final concept:

Four config layers, highest priority first:
1. .joy/config.yaml -- personal per-project settings, gitignored. Created by joy config set on first use.
2. ~/.config/joy/config.yaml -- personal global settings, cross-project. joy config set writes here if it exists and no .joy/ directory is present.
3. .joy/config.defaults.yaml -- committed project defaults, optional. Team can set shared baseline (e.g. interaction level). Whoever changes this knows what they are doing.
4. Code defaults -- hardcoded in joy binary, always present.

Fallback: 1 > 2 > 3 > 4. Only the delta is stored at each level.

Changes needed:
- joy init: add .joy/config.yaml to .gitignore
- joy config set: write to .joy/config.yaml (create if missing). If ~/.config/joy/config.yaml exists and no .joy/ dir, write there.
- joy config get: merge all layers, return resolved value
- joy config: show resolved config with indication of source per value (optional, nice to have)
- Rename current committed .joy/config.yaml to .joy/config.defaults.yaml in existing projects (migration)

What stays unchanged:
- .joy/project.yaml -- committed, project-wide. Managed by joy project set/get (JOY-0002).
- No /etc/joy/ level -- not needed until system packages exist.

Supersedes earlier discussion about --global/--local flags and config.local.yaml." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
